ProMED-PORT <promed@promedmail.org>

******
[3] Argentina
Date: 8 Apr 2009
Source: MSNBC [summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/30115212/>


Health Minister Graciela Ocana said Wednesday [8 Apr 2009] that a
dengue outbreak in the country has worsened to an epidemic, as nearly
8000 people are officially reported to be infected with the disease.
"Dengue is here to stay," Ocana said.

While the Health Ministry says the northern province of Chaco, one of
the worst hit, has registered 3590 cases, Amalsi Ruiz, a spokesman
for the provincial town of Charata, said nearly 4 times as many
people are infected, based on house-to-house surveys and hospital
visits. In total, 6 people have died, including 3 infected with the
severe hemorrhagic variant, which accounts for a fraction of dengue
cases.

The Health Ministry has launched a national campaign to educate
people on dengue prevention, including wearing insect repellant and
covering exposed body parts with thick clothing.

Authorities say Argentina's worst outbreak since the disease
reappeared in the country in 1997 is linked to an epidemic in
neighboring Bolivia, which has registered 51 000 cases.

--
Communicated by:
Health Map Alerts via
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Dengue is spreading in Argentina. La Nacion in its 11 Apr 2009
edition (in Spanish)
<http://www.lanacion.com.py/noticias-239891-2009-04-11.htm>
indicated that unofficial numbers place dengue-related deaths at 10
since the outbreak began in January 2009. The 1st locally acquired
dengue case has been reported in the populous Buenos Aires province.
Salta, Chaco and Catamarca are the most affected provinces, with 3506
cases confirmed by laboratory tests or epidemiological relationship.
Of these, 42 percent are from Charata city.

Telam, in its 7 Apr 2009 edition (in Spanish)
<http://www.telam.com.ar/vernota.php?tipo=N&idPub=141063&id=285185&dis=1&sec=1>,
reported 69 dengue cases, with an additional 64 under investigation,
in the city of Buenos Aires. The number of cases has doubled in a
week, but all were acquired outside the city. Also, there have been
43 locally acquired dengue cases in Corrientes, as well as new cases
in Santiago del Estero and in Santa Fe provinces.

Clarin.com reported on 7 Apr 2009 (in Spanish)
<http://www.clarin.com/diario/2009/04/07/sociedad/s-01892767.htm>
that there were 238 dengue cases in Buenos Aires city, all imported
from northern Argentina.

It is not clear why there have been consistent discrepancies in the
numbers of dengue cases reported in Argentina during this outbreak.
There appears to be significant under reporting in the official data,
as local health officials contend.

A map of Argentina showing the provinces mentioned can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/argentina_pol_1996.pdf>.
A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Argentina can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/r/008K>.
